§ Definition ⦉
¶ ⦊
  ‖ Given two distinct points $x$ and $y$ in $𝗥^n$, the ❬line❭
    through $x$ and $y$ is the set of points expressable as the
    sum of $x$ and $α(y-x)$ where $α ∈ 𝗥$. ⦉
⦉

¶ ⦊
  ‖ In other words, the line through $x$ and $y$ is the set
    ◇ ⦊
      ‖ \Set{z ∈ 𝗥^n}{∃ α ∈ 𝗥, z = x + α(y - x)} = \Set{x
        + α(y-x)}{α ∈ 𝗥} ⦉
    ⦉⦉

  ‖ The second expression is notation for the first, and is
    called the ❬set-generator notation❭. ⦉

  ‖ Notice that if $z = x + α(y-x)$, then
    ◇ ⦊
      ‖ z = (1 - α)x + αy, ⦉
    ⦉
    where $α ∈ 𝗥$ and $x, y ∈ 𝗥^n$. ⦉

  ‖ This highlights the obvious (and obviously desirable) property
    that the definition is symmetric in $x$ and $y$. ⦉
⦉

